05524nam a22006975i 9780822382584DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19921992ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223825847 a10.1515/97808223825842doi  a(DE-B1597)551933  a(OCoLC)1136208523  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aGR110.V8bH47 1992 7aHEA0110002bisacsh04a615.8/82/0975522000aHerbal and Magical Medicine :bTraditional Healing Today /cJames K. Kirkland, Charles W. Sullivan III, Karen Baldwin, Holly F. Matthews. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1992] 4cÂ©1992  a1 online resource (253 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: A Regional Approach and Multidisciplinary Perspective -- t1. Folk Medicine in Contemporary America -- t2. Traditional Healing Today: Moving Beyond Stereotypes -- t3. Talking Fire out of Burns: A Magico-Religious Healing Tradition -- t4. Parallels Between Magico-Religious Healing and Clinical Hypnosis Therapy -- t5. Doctors and Root Doctors: Patients Who Use Both -- t6. Rootwork from the Clinician's Perspective -- t7. The Cultural Epidemiology of Spiritual Heart Trouble -- t8. Herbal Medicine Among the Lumbee Indians -- t9. Childbirth Education and Traditional Beliefs About Pregnancy and Childbirth -- t10. Aesthetic Agency in the Folk Medical Practices and Remembrances of North Carolinians -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHerbal and Magical Medicine draws on perspectives from folklore, anthropology, psychology, medicine, and botany to describe the traditional medical beliefs and practices among Native, Anglo- and African Americans in eastern North Carolina and Virginia. In documenting the vitality of such seemingly unusual healing traditions as talking the fire out of burns, wart-curing, blood-stopping, herbal healing, and rootwork, the contributors to this volume demonstrate how the region's folk medical systems operate in tandem with scientific biomedicine.The authors provide illuminating commentary on the major forms of naturopathic and magico-religious medicine practiced in the United States. Other essays explain the persistence of these traditions in our modern technological society and address the bases of folk medical concepts of illness and treatment and the efficacy of particular pratices. The collection suggests a model for collaborative research on traditional medicine that can be replicated in other parts of the country. An extensive bibliography reveals the scope and variety of research in the field.Contributors. Karen Baldwin, Richard Blaustein, Linda Camino, Edward M. Croom Jr., David Hufford, James W. Kirland, Peter Lichstein, Holly F. Mathews, Robert Sammons, C. W. Sullivan III  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aTraditional medicinezNorth Carolina. 0aTraditional medicinezVirginia. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Herbal Medications.2bisacsh1 aBaldwin, Karen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSullivan, C, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHufford, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCroom, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMathews, Holly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKirkland, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaldwin, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKirkland, James K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCamino, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatthews, Holly F., eedit